		<div class="post" id="post-1978538">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,1978538)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-1978538">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/lumancer" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(662776); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=662776&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610203733" alt="Lumancer" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=662776)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/lumancer" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(662776); return false;" >Lumancer</a></span> <span class="odate time_1393436498 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">26 Feb 2014 17:41</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1978538">
									

<p>I know this was meant to be a comic interlude, but something about the piece has really solidified the reasons why this whole vision of the GOC has been bugging me. There's an increasingly large disparity between the content that formed my first impressions of the GOC and the group that appears in these tales. I could cite specific articles and such, but what it all boils down to is that we've collectively pointed to the GOC for the &quot;destroy, destroy, destroy&quot; mindset- and as a foil to make the Foundation seem reasonable by comparison- for a very long time. This version of the GOC (hereafter &quot;new GOC&quot;) is a flagrant contradiction of that entire notion:</p>
<ul>
<li>The SCPF is clearly less reasonable than new GOC, though a big part of this appears to be a much friendlier supernatural universe than that implied by the mainlist.</li>
<li>There's no logical reason for the Wanderer's Library types to refer to new GOC as &quot;The Bookburners&quot; when employment opportunities are ostensibly at least as likely as extermination.</li>
<li>Conversely, given how widely magic seems to be used by new GOC, I'm having a hard time justifying the notion that the SCPF is willing to work with them at all.</li>
<li>Most confusing to me, the very existence of new GOC as a fairly paranormal-tolerant UN-backed organization calls into question why the SCPF is permitted to exist (independently) at all. I may be stretching here, but if they're willing to seek diplomatic relations with Eugenio of all things then the Foundations is arguably guilty of war crimes at minimum- and much worse when shit like Tophet or Montauk is brought into consideration.</li>
</ul>
<p>I know, I know, &quot;there is no canon&quot;, but this is starting to stick in my craw as badly as&#8230; I dunno, the entire O5 counsel turning out to be the Olympian gods or something. In isolation, new GOC is pretty cool, and in the Unfounded canon in particular the slightly more reasonable riff on their old selves made for some really awesome world building. But outside of that canon, the very fact that they <em>are</em> the GOC and not some other group clashes really strangely with a lot of precedent.</p>

							</div>

								
